In article <2ev1pj$fd3@nz12.rz.uni-karlsruhe.de> uknf@rzstud1.rz.uni-karlsruhe.de (Olaf Titz) writes:
>In article <2ek0km$n6l@apakabar.cc.columbia.edu>,
>David Neal Messina <dnm9@bonjour.cc.columbia.edu> wrote:
>> PGP will do what you describe in the first paragraph -- you must
>> specify the multiple users, and the program will encode your message
>> with each recipient's respective public key.  
>
>Then you have a file containing distinguishable blocks of the same
>message encrypted with (a potentially large number of?) different
>(session) keys. Is it possible to draw conclusions (retrieving the
>plaintext, or worse, retrieving the private keys) from comparing
>these ciphertexts, or is IDEA invulnerable to this kind of attack?

no, you end up with a file with several RSA encrypted messages
of the same plaintext and a single block of IDEA encrypted text.
For example if you are sending to x,y and z,  and Ki is the IDEA
key (random):

        { Ki }Kx
        { Ki }Ky
        { Ki }Kz
        { DATA }Ki

